        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="3">
            <title>service procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, personal injury, or death, park the vehicle on a flat level surface,
                        set the parking brake, turn the engine off, and chock the wheels.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or death from hot coolant or steam use only the following procedure
                        to remove the pressure cap from the radiator or expansion tank. Allow the engine to cool first.
                        Wrap a thick heavy cloth around the cap. Push down, loosen the cap slowly to the first notch
                        position; then pause a moment to allow pressure to release through the over flow tube. After the
                        pressure has been released, the pressure cap may be removed.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drain the engine coolant into a suitable, clean container.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>A small number of engines were put into service with the block heater harness but without the
                        block heater. The block heater bore is sealed with a freeze plug.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the block heater or freeze plug and Loctite sealant, if so equipped, located
                    forward of the engine control unit (ECU)/injector drive module (IDM) on the driver's side of the
                    engine (Figure 1).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0690701" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0690701.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Freeze Plug or Block Heater Removed Shown at Arrow</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the freeze plug bore and surrounding area with fine emery cloth moving in a
                    circular motion around the opening. Do not move laterally across the bore. Ensure the bore is clean
                    and smooth.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate the block heater seal ring with O-ring lubricant and install the block heater
                    (Figure 2). Make sure the heating element is not in contact with any metal inside the engine block.
                    When the block heater is inserted properly into the bore, tighten the Allen head screw to 40 to 45
                    Lbf-in (4.5 to 5 Nm) to lock it in position.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0690702" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0690702.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Install Block Heater</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Allen Head Locking Screw</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect the power lead to the block heater and secure it with the round nut (Figure
                    3).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0690703" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0690703.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Connect Power Lead</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Refill the cooling system with the coolant that was drained in Step 1.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start the engine, run to operating temperature and check for leaks.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
